@flexiarg equity/visible-impact
@title A Programme That Cannot See Its Own Effects Cannot Learn
@keywords feedback, monitoring, evaluation, impact, reflexive monitoring, NPT, Ostrom, backward propagation, reflexivity
@audience programme designers, evaluators, funders, futon coordination layer
@tone analytic-foundational
@style pattern
@references [equity/ARGUMENT equity/contribution-pathways equity/confident-adaptation]

! conclusion: A programme learns and sustains motivation only when feedback is structured, visible, and shared across institutions. Without cross-institutional monitoring, the backward propagation that makes the whole system a learning system does not reach the outermost level — and the equity loop does not close.
  + context: A distributed programme needs evidence of its downstream impact to improve its own design, sustain trainer motivation, and justify continued institutional support. In NPT terms this is Reflexive Monitoring (4.2 Communal Appraisal): shared mechanisms for evaluating what is working and what is not. In the whole-board-play analogy, Patterns 1-4 gave the agent the rules, the conditions to play, a way for local learning to propagate into shared materials, and a route into co-governance. This final pattern asks whether the whole system can see its own effects and adjust — whether backward propagation reaches all the way from outcomes to architecture.
  + IF:
    The programme has resolved the preceding conditions: expectations are clear (Pattern 1), delivery is protected (Pattern 2), materials are stewarded (Pattern 3), and trainers have contribution pathways into co-governance (Pattern 4). Local learning propagates into materials and governance. But the system's learning operates only at the level of individual adaptations and community conversation. It does not yet have a way to see its own aggregate effects — across institutions, across cohorts, across time.
  + HOWEVER:
    Feedback mechanisms are thin. Trainers rely on optional post-session surveys that yield only positive or absent responses. Cross-institutional sharing is limited: formal channels exist but go largely unused. No one performs cross-institutional analysis. The programme cannot demonstrate impact to the institutions it depends on for support. An entire evaluation workstream was funded but the evaluation chain — from instrument design through data collection to cross-institutional analysis to feedback — was not built. This is the deepest failure of backward propagation: the system plays, the system learns locally, but the aggregate signal — what is actually working across the whole landscape — never reaches the actors who could adjust the system's architecture. Without this signal, the agents within the system cannot know whether their becoming is on track. Feedback is not just a management tool; it is what makes the whole system reflexive rather than blind.
  + THEN:
    The evaluation chain is designed before the first delivery event. Roles are assigned explicitly at each link: who designs instruments, who collects data, who analyses cross-institutional patterns, who reports back to trainers and institutional leads. Shared feedback converts isolated impressions into programme-level learning. The chain is resourced end-to-end, not just at the instrument-design end. The feedback does not stop at the funders' desk — it propagates back to trainers, to institutional leads, to the scaffold itself (Pattern 1), completing the circuit. This is the whole-board view: the system sees its own aggregate play and adjusts.
  + BECAUSE:
    Sen: Feedback is a conversion factor for persistence. Without visible consequences, capability decays into isolated effort. But more than that: feedback is what allows the system to assess whether its conversion factors are actually working — whether the scaffold (Pattern 1) is giving the right form, whether provisioning (Pattern 2) is sufficient, whether the commons (Pattern 3) is healthy, whether co-governance (Pattern 4) is real. Without this assessment, the equity loop is flying blind.

    Whole-board play: This is the final level of backward propagation. Pattern 3 propagates local learning into shared materials (updating the weights from individual games). Pattern 4 propagates trainer experience into programme governance (modifying the architecture). Pattern 5 propagates aggregate outcomes into the system's self-understanding (seeing the whole board). In AlphaZero, this is analogous to meta-learning: not just learning from games, but learning whether the learning process itself is producing the right kind of improvement. Without this level, the system can improve locally but cannot assess whether it is improving globally. It can play but cannot see its own play.

    Ostrom: This is the monitoring problem in its strongest form. Monitoring and information flows across action arenas determine whether the programme can learn and adjust. The learning chain crosses multiple actors and no single trainer can sustain it alone. An evaluation workstream is not an evaluation chain. The chain requires specific actors at each link — instrument designer, data collector, cross-institutional analyst, feedback reporter — and each link must be resourced. When any one is missing, the loop does not close. This is the most coordination-intensive condition and the most consistently absent — not because no one wanted to monitor, but because the monitoring chain has too many links for the current governance structure to sustain.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Design the evaluation chain before the first delivery event, not as a retrofit
    - Assign named roles at each link of the chain
    - Resource cross-institutional analysis explicitly — it is the central link and the most absent
    - Design feedback to propagate back to practitioners, not just upward to funders
    - Test: can the programme produce one cross-institutional learning report within its first year?
    - This requires a multi-actor chain (very high coordination, 6+ actors) and is the final condition
  + INVARIANT-STATEMENT:
    The programme has a complete evaluation chain from instrument design through cross-institutional analysis to feedback, with a named actor at each link and explicit resourcing for the cross-institutional analysis step. Feedback propagates to trainers and institutional leads, not only to funders.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Blind system: the programme cannot see its own aggregate effects
    - Thin feedback: optional surveys yield only positive or absent responses
    - Informal-only evidence: trainers rely on "you can kind of tell whether people are engaged"
    - Broken chain: instruments exist but no one collects, analyses, or reports cross-institutionally
    - Upward-only feedback: results reach funders but never propagate back to practitioners
    - Motivation erosion: trainers cannot see whether their effort matters beyond anecdote
    - Funded ambition without architecture: an entire evaluation workstream exists on paper but the handoff chain is not built
  + ANCESTORS:
    - UKRN T3 transcript evidence: T2B ("I have no other ways of getting feedback short of people filling in the feedback form")
    - UKRN T3 transcript evidence: T2B ("As we get like a few answers and nobody says this was terrible, I generally think it's gone quite well")
    - UKRN T3 transcript evidence: T2B ("Even if you then don't get the feedback survey, you can kind of tell whether people are engaged")
    - REDF proposal: Workstream 2 planned NPT-aligned surveys, case studies, ORCID tracking, dashboards, trial framework
    - REDF proposal: cross-institutional evaluation was the central ambition and the most completely absent in practice
  + DERIVATION:
    Derived from NPT Reflexive Monitoring (4.2 Communal Appraisal) via the UKRN T3 analysis.
    Mapped to the equity loop at the feedback joint: the mechanism that tells the system whether the loop is closing.
    Deepened via whole-board play: this is the outermost level of backward propagation — the system seeing its own aggregate play and adjusting. Without it, the system can improve locally but cannot assess whether it is improving globally.
    Ostrom: monitoring and information flows across action arenas determine whether the programme can learn.
    Coordination requirement: Very high (6+ actor chain).
